  "prompt": "When is surge pricing on Uber generally in effect in Detroit and how high does it go?",
  "response": "Surge pricing on Uber in Detroit, as in other cities, typically occurs during periods of high demand when the number of riders exceeds the number of available drivers. This can happen during:\n\n1. **Rush Hours**: Morning and evening commutes (usually 7\u20139 AM and 4\u20137 PM).\n2. **Weekend Nights**: Especially Friday and Saturday evenings (e.g., 10 PM\u20132 AM) when people are going out or returning from events.\n3. **Special Events**: Concerts, sports games, festivals, or other large gatherings.\n4. **Bad Weather**: During snowstorms, heavy rain, or extreme cold when fewer drivers are on the road.\n\nThe **surge multiplier** indicates how much higher the fare is compared to standard pricing. In Detroit, surge multipliers can range from **1.2x to 3x or higher** depending on demand. In extreme cases, such as during major events or severe weather, prices can spike even higher, potentially reaching **5x or more**.\n\nTo avoid surprises, always check the app for surge notifications and consider alternative transportation options during peak times.",
